    {
      "type": "text",
      "text": "* 5. Chains of (in)equalities\n\nAs a last step of a proof in Analysis, we often have a chain of (in)equalities. Consider for instance a case in which we would like to show that for all $ε : \\mathbb{R}$, if $ε > 0$ then $\\min(\\epsilon, 1) ≤ 2$. \n\nHere are the statement and a possible proof in Waterproof. Note that we need to write `Rmin x y` for the minimum of two real numbers $x$ and $y$."
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "text": "\nLemma example_inequalities :\n  ∀ ε : ℝ, ε > 0 ⇒ Rmin ε 1 ≤ 2."
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "text": "Proof.\nTake ε : ℝ.\nAssume ε_gt_0 : (ε > 0).\nRewrite inequality (Rmin ε 1) \"≤\" (1)\n                              \"≤\" (2).\nQed."
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "text": "\nNote how we used the tactic `Rewrite inequality` to represent the chain of inequalities\n\n$$\\min(\\epsilon, 1) ≤ 1 ≤ 2.$$\n\nThe `Rewrite inequality` tactic expects a chain of (in)equalities. the (in)equality signs need to be placed between quotes (like `\"≥\"`), and usually the terms (such as `x^2`) need to be put in between parentheses (as in `(4 + 0)` rather than just `4 + 0`)."
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "text": "** Try it yourself: chains of (in)equalities"
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "text": "Lemma exercise_inequalities :\n  ∀ ε : ℝ, ε > 0 ⇒ Rmin (ε / 2) 1 ≤ ε.\n  \nProof."
    },
    {
      "type": "input",
      "start": true,
      "id": "input-4"
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Write your solution here..."
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
